{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"06f54f2a-afbf-4d31-b998-47c038525cec","content":"Here are the MSBuild evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n---\n\n### 1. **File I/O During Evaluation** (High Impact)\n**Line 13 in `EvalHeavy.csproj`:**\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nProperty functions that perform file I/O execute during *evaluation*, not build. This blocks the evaluator and doesn't cache well across re-evaluations. Prefer reading files as a target/task at build time.\n\n---\n\n### 2. **Recursive Wildcard Glob** (High Impact)\n**Line 9:**\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\n`**\\*.*` forces the evaluator to walk the entire directory tree. This is expensive in large repos and invalidates the MSBuild evaluation cache whenever *any* file changes.\n\n---\n\n### 3. **Deeply Chained Imports** (Moderate Impact)\n```\nEvalHeavy.csproj → level1.props → level2.props → level3.props\n```\nThree levels of nested imports. Each import is resolved and parsed sequentially during evaluation. In larger projects this pattern compounds. Flatten where possible.\n\n---\n\n### Summary\n\n| Pattern | Mechanism | Fix |\n|---------|-----------|-----|\n| `File::ReadAllText` in property | Disk I/O at eval time | Move to a target using `ReadLinesFromFile` task |\n| `**\\*.*` glob | Full directory walk at eval time | Narrow the glob or move to a target |\n| Nested `.props` imports | Sequential parse chain | Flatten into fewer files |\n\nThe recursive glob and the property-function file read are the biggest offenders — they scale with repo size and re-run on every evaluation pass.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"26f2038d-80f0-4452-95d9-76fa2b21fdec","outputTokens":450,"requestId":"0423:215959:B3E6D4:D0E42A:69F2AE44"},"id":"bd12bbb7-cc73-42dd-982a-031265378209","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:20:15.956Z","parentId":"72848864-2653-4eb1-b0b7-130fb2c19b04"}
